{"paragraphs":[{"cues":[{"time":760,"text":"Extraordinary claims\nrequire extraordinary evidence,"},{"time":5280,"text":"and it is my job,\nmy responsibility, as an astronomer"},{"time":10000,"text":"to remind people that alien hypotheses\nshould always be a last resort."}]},{"cues":[{"time":17440,"text":"Now, I want to tell you\na story about that."},{"time":19600,"text":"It involves data from a NASA mission,"},{"time":23200,"text":"ordinary people and one of the most\nextraordinary stars in our galaxy."}]},{"cues":[{"time":29800,"text":"It began in 2009 with the launch\nof NASA's Kepler mission."},{"time":34000,"text":"Kepler's main scientific objective"},{"time":36080,"text":"was to find planets\noutside of our solar system."},{"time":39080,"text":"It did this by staring\nat a single field in the sky,"},{"time":42680,"text":"this one, with all the tiny boxes."},{"time":45480,"text":"And in this one field,"},{"time":46920,"text":"it monitored the brightness\nof over 150,000 stars"},{"time":51360,"text":"continuously for four years,"},{"time":53800,"text":"taking a data point every 30 minutes."},{"time":58480,"text":"It was looking for what\nastronomers call a transit."},{"time":61520,"text":"This is when the planet's orbit\nis aligned in our line of sight,"},{"time":66560,"text":"just so that the planet\ncrosses in front of a star."},{"time":70720,"text":"And when this happens,\nit blocks out a tiny bit of starlight,"},{"time":75120,"text":"which you can see as a dip in this curve."}]},{"cues":[{"time":79600,"text":"And so the team at NASA\nhad developed very sophisticated computers"},{"time":84040,"text":"to search for transits\nin all the Kepler data."}]},{"cues":[{"time":88160,"text":"At the same time\nof the first data release,"},{"time":92080,"text":"astronomers at Yale\nwere wondering an interesting thing:"},{"time":96240,"text":"What if computers missed something?"}]},{"cues":[{"time":101040,"text":"And so we launched the citizen\nscience project called Planet Hunters"},{"time":105760,"text":"to have people look at the same data."},{"time":109600,"text":"The human brain has an amazing ability\nfor pattern recognition,"},{"time":113400,"text":"sometimes even better than a computer."},{"time":115640,"text":"However, there was a lot\nof skepticism around this."},{"time":118200,"text":"My colleague, Debra Fischer,\nfounder of the Planet Hunters project,"},{"time":121760,"text":"said that people at the time were saying,"},{"time":123760,"text":"\"You're crazy. There's no way\nthat a computer will miss a signal.\""},{"time":127560,"text":"And so it was on, the classic\nhuman versus machine gamble."},{"time":131800,"text":"And if we found one planet,\nwe would be thrilled."},{"time":135000,"text":"When I joined the team four years ago,"},{"time":137480,"text":"we had already found a couple."},{"time":140360,"text":"And today, with the help\nof over 300,000 science enthusiasts,"},{"time":145040,"text":"we have found dozens,"},{"time":146840,"text":"and we've also found\none of the most mysterious stars"},{"time":150120,"text":"in our galaxy."}]},{"cues":[{"time":153040,"text":"So to understand this,"},{"time":154520,"text":"let me show you what a normal transit\nin Kepler data looks like."},{"time":158680,"text":"On this graph on the left-hand side\nyou have the amount of light,"},{"time":162080,"text":"and on the bottom is time."},{"time":163960,"text":"The white line\nis light just from the star,"},{"time":167040,"text":"what astronomers call a light curve."},{"time":169440,"text":"Now, when a planet transits a star,\nit blocks out a little bit of this light,"},{"time":173320,"text":"and the depth of this transit\nreflects the size of the object itself."},{"time":178800,"text":"And so, for example, let's take Jupiter."},{"time":181440,"text":"Planets don't get\nmuch bigger than Jupiter."},{"time":183600,"text":"Jupiter will make a one percent drop\nin a star's brightness."},{"time":187400,"text":"Earth, on the other hand,\nis 11 times smaller than Jupiter,"},{"time":191600,"text":"and the signal\nis barely visible in the data."}]},{"cues":[{"time":194440,"text":"So back to our mystery."},{"time":196520,"text":"A few years ago, Planet Hunters were\nsifting through data looking for transits,"},{"time":201200,"text":"and they spotted a mysterious signal\ncoming from the star KIC 8462852."},{"time":207920,"text":"The observations in May of 2009\nwere the first they spotted,"},{"time":211960,"text":"and they started talking about this\nin the discussion forums."}]},{"cues":[{"time":215320,"text":"They said and object like Jupiter"},{"time":217440,"text":"would make a drop like this\nin the star's light,"},{"time":220360,"text":"but they were also saying it was giant."},{"time":223720,"text":"You see, transits normally\nonly last for a few hours,"},{"time":226960,"text":"and this one lasted for almost a week."}]},{"cues":[{"time":229880,"text":"They were also saying\nthat it looks asymmetric,"},{"time":233440,"text":"meaning that instead of the clean,\nU-shaped dip that we saw with Jupiter,"},{"time":237720,"text":"it had this strange slope\nthat you can see on the left side."},{"time":241240,"text":"This seemed to indicate"},{"time":242600,"text":"that whatever was getting in the way\nand blocking the starlight"},{"time":246000,"text":"was not circular like a planet."},{"time":249240,"text":"There are few more dips that happened,"},{"time":251160,"text":"but for a couple of years,\nit was pretty quiet."}]},{"cues":[{"time":254400,"text":"And then in March of 2011, we see this."},{"time":259120,"text":"The star's light drops\nby a whole 15 percent,"},{"time":263240,"text":"and this is huge compared to a planet,"},{"time":265440,"text":"which would only make a one percent drop."},{"time":268480,"text":"We described this feature\nas both smooth and clean."},{"time":272040,"text":"It also is asymmetric,"},{"time":274080,"text":"having a gradual dimming\nthat lasts almost a week,"},{"time":276760,"text":"and then it snaps right back up to normal\nin just a matter of days."}]},{"cues":[{"time":280920,"text":"And again, after this, not much happens"},{"time":285200,"text":"until February of 2013."},{"time":288920,"text":"Things start to get really crazy."},{"time":291560,"text":"There is a huge complex of dips\nin the light curve that appear,"},{"time":296080,"text":"and they last for like a hundred days,"},{"time":298240,"text":"all the way up\ninto the Kepler mission's end."},{"time":301280,"text":"These dips have variable shapes."},{"time":303280,"text":"Some are very sharp, and some are broad,"},{"time":305520,"text":"and they also have variable durations."},{"time":307800,"text":"Some last just for a day or two,\nand some for more than a week."},{"time":312120,"text":"And there's also up and down trends\nwithin some of these dips,"},{"time":315480,"text":"almost like several independent events\nwere superimposed on top of each other."},{"time":320920,"text":"And at this time, this star drops\nin its brightness over 20 percent."},{"time":327160,"text":"This means that whatever\nis blocking its light"},{"time":329327,"text":"has an area of over 1,000 times\nthe area of our planet Earth."}]},{"cues":[{"time":334200,"text":"This is truly remarkable."},{"time":337360,"text":"And so the citizen scientists,\nwhen they saw this,"},{"time":339760,"text":"they notified the science team\nthat they found something weird enough"},{"time":343480,"text":"that it might be worth following up."},{"time":346680,"text":"And so when the science team looked at it,"},{"time":348760,"text":"we're like, \"Yeah, there's probably\njust something wrong with the data.\""},{"time":352165,"text":"But we looked really, really, really hard,"},{"time":354720,"text":"and the data were good."},{"time":358680,"text":"And so what was happening\nhad to be astrophysical,"},{"time":361800,"text":"meaning that something in space\nwas getting in the way"},{"time":365480,"text":"and blocking starlight."},{"time":368240,"text":"And so at this point,"},{"time":369480,"text":"we set out to learn\neverything we could about the star"},{"time":372080,"text":"to see if we could find any clues\nto what was going on."},{"time":375720,"text":"And the citizen scientists\nwho helped us in this discovery,"},{"time":378920,"text":"they joined along for the ride"},{"time":380480,"text":"watching science in action firsthand."}]},{"cues":[{"time":385000,"text":"First, somebody said, you know,\nwhat if this star was very young"},{"time":390480,"text":"and it still had the cloud of material\nit was born from surrounding it."},{"time":395040,"text":"And then somebody else said,"},{"time":396480,"text":"well, what if the star\nhad already formed planets,"},{"time":399280,"text":"and two of these planets had collided,"},{"time":401520,"text":"similar to the Earth-Moon forming event."},{"time":404440,"text":"Well, both of these theories\ncould explain part of the data,"},{"time":408000,"text":"but the difficulties were that the star\nshowed no signs of being young,"},{"time":411440,"text":"and there was no glow\nfrom any of the material"},{"time":414400,"text":"that was heated up by the star's light,"},{"time":416520,"text":"and you would expect this\nif the star was young"},{"time":419400,"text":"or if there was a collision\nand a lot of dust was produced."},{"time":423800,"text":"And so somebody else said,"},{"time":425440,"text":"well, how about a huge swarm of comets"},{"time":430440,"text":"that are passing by this star\nin a very elliptical orbit?"},{"time":434120,"text":"Well, it ends up that this is actually\nconsistent with our observations."},{"time":440000,"text":"But I agree, it does feel\na little contrived."},{"time":443280,"text":"You see, it would take hundreds of comets"},{"time":446600,"text":"to reproduce what we're observing."},{"time":449200,"text":"And these are only the comets"},{"time":450800,"text":"that happen to pass\nbetween us and the star."},{"time":453440,"text":"And so in reality, we're talking\nthousands to tens of thousands of comets."},{"time":459920,"text":"But of all the bad ideas we had,"},{"time":463400,"text":"this one was the best."},{"time":465560,"text":"And so we went ahead\nand published our findings."}]},{"cues":[{"time":468520,"text":"Now, let me tell you, this was one\nof the hardest papers I ever wrote."},{"time":472760,"text":"Scientists are meant to publish results,"},{"time":475120,"text":"and this situation was far from that."},{"time":477960,"text":"And so we decided\nto give it a catchy title,"},{"time":481120,"text":"and we called it: \"Where's The Flux?\""},{"time":483320,"text":"I will let you work out the acronym."}]},{"cues":[{"time":486160,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":490840,"text":"So this isn't the end of the story."},{"time":492560,"text":"Around the same time\nI was writing this paper,"},{"time":494760,"text":"I met with a colleague\nof mine, Jason Wright,"},{"time":496920,"text":"and he was also writing a paper\non Kepler data."},{"time":499160,"text":"And he was saying that with Kepler's\nextreme precision,"},{"time":503360,"text":"it could actually detect\nalien megastructures around stars,"},{"time":508240,"text":"but it didn't."},{"time":510520,"text":"And then I showed him this weird data\nthat our citizen scientists had found,"},{"time":515559,"text":"and he said to me,"},{"time":516799,"text":"\"Aw crap, Tabby."},{"time":518600,"text":"Now I have to rewrite my paper.\""}]},{"cues":[{"time":522440,"text":"So yes, the natural\nexplanations were weak,"},{"time":526480,"text":"and we were curious now."},{"time":528080,"text":"So we had to find a way\nto rule out aliens."},{"time":531280,"text":"So together, we convinced\na colleague of ours"},{"time":534160,"text":"who works on SETI, the Search\nfor Extraterrestrial Intelligence,"},{"time":537440,"text":"that this would be\nan extraordinary target to pursue."},{"time":542480,"text":"We wrote a proposal to observe the star"},{"time":544880,"text":"with the world's largest radio telescope\nat the Green Bank Observatory."}]},{"cues":[{"time":549080,"text":"A couple months later,"},{"time":550480,"text":"news of this proposal\ngot leaked to the press"},{"time":555760,"text":"and now there are thousands of articles,"},{"time":559240,"text":"over 10,000 articles, on this star alone."},{"time":562400,"text":"And if you search Google Images,"},{"time":564920,"text":"this is what you'll find."}]},{"cues":[{"time":567600,"text":"Now, you may be wondering,\nOK, Tabby, well,"},{"time":570120,"text":"how do aliens actually explain\nthis light curve?"},{"time":574000,"text":"OK, well, imagine a civilization\nthat's much more advanced than our own."},{"time":579320,"text":"In this hypothetical circumstance,"},{"time":582680,"text":"this civilization would have exhausted\nthe energy supply of their home planet,"},{"time":587360,"text":"so where could they get more energy?"},{"time":589560,"text":"Well, they have a host star\njust like we have a sun,"},{"time":593240,"text":"and so if they were able\nto capture more energy from this star,"},{"time":597320,"text":"then that would solve their energy needs."},{"time":599800,"text":"So they would go\nand build huge structures."},{"time":603240,"text":"These giant megastructures,"},{"time":606040,"text":"like ginormous solar panels,\nare called Dyson spheres."}]},{"cues":[{"time":610440,"text":"This image above"},{"time":611760,"text":"are lots of artists' impressions\nof Dyson spheres."},{"time":614960,"text":"It's really hard to provide perspective\non the vastness of these things,"},{"time":620000,"text":"but you can think of it this way."},{"time":621840,"text":"The Earth-Moon distance\nis a quarter of a million miles."},{"time":626040,"text":"The simplest element\non one of these structures"},{"time":629960,"text":"is 100 times that size."},{"time":633400,"text":"They're enormous."},{"time":636080,"text":"And now imagine one of these structures\nin motion around a star."},{"time":640520,"text":"You can see how it would produce\nanomalies in the data"},{"time":643640,"text":"such as uneven, unnatural looking dips."}]},{"cues":[{"time":646880,"text":"But it remains that even\nalien megastructures"},{"time":650880,"text":"cannot defy the laws of physics."},{"time":653320,"text":"You see, anything that uses\na lot of energy"},{"time":657800,"text":"is going to produce heat,"},{"time":660840,"text":"and we don't observe this."},{"time":662840,"text":"But it could be something as simple"},{"time":664560,"text":"as they're just reradiating it away\nin another direction,"},{"time":668040,"text":"just not at Earth."}]},{"cues":[{"time":671000,"text":"Another idea that's one\nof my personal favorites"},{"time":674320,"text":"is that we had just witnessed\nan interplanetary space battle"},{"time":678120,"text":"and the catastrophic\ndestruction of a planet."},{"time":682520,"text":"Now, I admit that this\nwould produce a lot of dust"},{"time":685800,"text":"that we don't observe."},{"time":687720,"text":"But if we're already invoking aliens\nin this explanation,"},{"time":692080,"text":"then who is to say they didn't\nefficiently clean up all this mess"},{"time":695800,"text":"for recycling purposes?"}]},{"cues":[{"time":697360,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":698400,"text":"You can see how this quickly\ncaptures your imagination."}]},{"cues":[{"time":703760,"text":"Well, there you have it."},{"time":705040,"text":"We're in a situation that could unfold"},{"time":708280,"text":"to be a natural phenomenon\nwe don't understand"},{"time":711720,"text":"or an alien technology\nwe don't understand."},{"time":715600,"text":"Personally, as a scientist,\nmy money is on the natural explanation."},{"time":722040,"text":"But don't get me wrong, I do think\nit would be awesome to find aliens."},{"time":726800,"text":"Either way, there is something new\nand really interesting to discover."}]},{"cues":[{"time":732040,"text":"So what happens next?"},{"time":733920,"text":"We need to continue to observe this star"},{"time":736600,"text":"to learn more about what's happening."},{"time":739040,"text":"But professional astronomers, like me,"},{"time":741640,"text":"we have limited resources\nfor this kind of thing,"},{"time":744480,"text":"and Kepler is on to a different mission."}]},{"cues":[{"time":747400,"text":"And I'm happy to say that once again,"},{"time":751640,"text":"citizen scientists have come in\nand saved the day."},{"time":755880,"text":"You see, this time,"},{"time":758360,"text":"amateur astronomers\nwith their backyard telescopes"},{"time":762120,"text":"stepped up immediately\nand started observing this star nightly"},{"time":766120,"text":"at their own facilities,"},{"time":767640,"text":"and I am so excited to see what they find."}]},{"cues":[{"time":771520,"text":"What's amazing to me is that this star\nwould have never been found by computers"},{"time":775720,"text":"because we just weren't looking\nfor something like this."},{"time":779400,"text":"And what's more exciting"},{"time":783680,"text":"is that there's more data to come."},{"time":786200,"text":"There are new missions that are coming up"},{"time":788200,"text":"that are observing millions more stars"},{"time":791840,"text":"all over the sky."}]},{"cues":[{"time":794280,"text":"And just think: What will it mean\nwhen we find another star like this?"},{"time":800520,"text":"And what will it mean\nif we don't find another star like this?"}]},{"cues":[{"time":805280,"text":"Thank you."}]},{"cues":[{"time":806520,"text":"(Applause)"}]}]}